#!/usr/bin/env python3
# =============================================================================
# kwin_mouse-clicks.py
# Generated by: Claude Sonnet 4.6
#
# Interactive mouse-click and keyboard monitor for building input_actions DSL.
#
# Runs in a Konsole session (via 'sg input -c "python3 kwin_mouse-clicks.py"'
# if the input group is not active in the current session token).
#
# Output format:
#
#   Mouse clicks:
#     # firefox  |  "Open File — Firefox"  |  abs(1234, 567)  |  rel(210, 44)
#     {WCLICK 210, 44}
#
#   Mouse drags (left-button):
#     # firefox  |  "Open File — Firefox"  |  abs(1234, 567) → abs(1390, 567)  |  rel(210, 44) → rel(366, 44)
#     {WDRAG 210, 44 to 366, 44}
#
#   Keyboard sequences (flushed on ENTER or ESC):
#     # firefox  |  "Open File — Firefox"  |  keyboard
#     /home/user/docs/{ENTER}
#
# The comment lines are for human reference.  The DSL lines paste directly
# into the input_actions property of a YAML setup file.
# Comment lines (starting with #) are ignored by the input_actions parser.
#
# Keyboard flush triggers:
#   ENTER  — adds {ENTER} to the buffer, then flushes and resets
#   ESC    — adds {ESC} to the buffer, then flushes and resets
#   Window change (any mouse click that lands on a different window) —
#             flushes the pending keyboard buffer before processing the click
#
# REQUIREMENTS:
#   python-evdev   (pip install evdev)
#   User must be in the 'input' group.  If the group is not in the current
#   session token after usermod + reboot (SDDM/PAM issue), use:
#     sg input -c "python3 kwin_mouse-clicks.py [OPTIONS]"
#
# USAGE:
#   python3 kwin_mouse-clicks.py [OPTIONS]
#   sg input -c "python3 kwin_mouse-clicks.py [OPTIONS]"
#
# OPTIONS:
#   --setup FILE       Setup/snapshot YAML to load known windows from.
#                      Defaults to default_setup from config.yaml.
#   --config FILE      Alternate wayland-desktop config file.
#   --log FILE         Also write output to FILE (write mode, ANSI stripped).
#   --no-dsl           Print comment lines only; suppress DSL token output.
#   --verbose          Also log mouse-move events (very noisy).
#   --drag-threshold N Minimum pixel displacement (in either axis) to treat a
#                      left-button press+release as a drag rather than a click.
#                      Default: 5.
#
# CONTROLS (while running):
#   Ctrl-C             Stop monitoring cleanly.
#
# INLINE COMMENTS:
#   Because all keystrokes are captured, you can annotate a recording session
#   by simply typing a comment at any time.  Type a pound sign, the comment
#   text, then press ENTER.  The script will emit a comment block in the
#   output and in the log file, for example:
#
#     # here is my comment{ENTER}
#
#   This is useful for marking sections of a complex workflow, reminding
#   yourself what a particular click sequence does, or noting which dialog
#   was open at the time.  The comment lines are ignored by the
#   input_actions parser when the YAML is replayed.
#
# KNOWN ISSUES:
#   Mouse-driven input (WCLICK / WRCLICK / WDRAG coordinates) is fragile.  The
#   coordinates are recorded relative to the top-left corner of the window
#   at the moment the click or drag was captured.  If the window is subsequently
#   resized, moved, or displayed at a different size (e.g. on a screen with
#   a different resolution or DPI), the relative coordinates will no longer
#   point to the intended target.  Review and update WCLICK / WDRAG coordinates
#   whenever the window layout or screen configuration changes.
#
#   Drag detection: the DSL line for a left-button action is emitted on button
#   release (not press), so that the final pointer position is known.  Short
#   movements within --drag-threshold pixels are logged as {WCLICK}; larger
#   movements are logged as {WDRAG}.
